node.text: A true pioneer in both underwater filmmaking and shark research, Valerie Taylor is a living legend whose life’s work has become the basis for much of what we know about sharks today. Follow this daring ocean explorer’s trajectory from champion spearfisher to passionate shark protector in Playing With Sharks, now streaming on @disneyplus

node.text: Rio De Janeiro, Brazil: Witness the inspiring story of Tuany, a 23-year-old ballet dancer who started a dance company for young girls in the middle of one of Rio De Janeiro’s most dangerous favelas. She gives students hope for a better future and a safe space away from the violent world around them.

node.text: Grand Caillou/Dulac, Louisiana, U.S.A.: Meet Chief Shirell, the first female chief of her southern Louisiana tribe. Her ancestors have lived on the land for hundreds of years, and they are now expected to be among the United States’ first climate refugees. Chief Shirell can’t stop the storms, but she is impacting the legacy of her ancestors, the lives of her community today and the future of her people.

node.text: Memphis, Tennessee, U.S.A.: Meet Kayla, who has dedicated her life to helping homeless transgender women of color in Memphis, Tennessee. Having experienced homelessness and violence herself, Kayla has created a safe community for these notoriously discriminated-against people. She is building more than two dozen houses across Memphis for transgender women who need safety and a place to call home.

node.text:
Photos by Elliot Ross @elliotstudio / In Vernon, an industrial area near downtown L.A., surfaces can be more than 15 degrees Fahrenheit (8°C) hotter than in leafy neighborhoods elsewhere in the city. Only a hundred or so people live in this sun-blasted place, but some 50,000 come here to work—many using public transport with stations and stops that are poorly protected from the sun. The need for heat mitigation strategies is becoming more apparent with each passing year as our planet warms rapidly. 

Writer @alejandrabee sums up the situation in the July issue's cover story: "By mid-century L.A. is expected to experience 22 days a year above 95 degrees Fahrenheit [35°C], more than triple the current number. The suburbs in the San Fernando Valley may see more than 90 days—a full quarter of the year. Heat already increases the risk of death in Los Angeles, even when it isn’t the proximate cause. During a short heat wave, the death rate from all causes rises by 8 percent above normal. After four or five days, that number swells to 25 percent—and up to 48 percent among older Black and Latino residents." For more on this story, click the link in our bio.

Photo by @dguttenfelder David Guttenfelder / Kaitlin Knutson of the organization Involve MN (left), hands a Thanksgiving meal to Christy Haanen, who lives in this tented encampment in a park in St. Paul. Before the pandemic, the police would force people to leave every few days and even destroy their shelters. “Not all of us choose to be out here,” Haanen says. “But many don’t have a family. They don’t have anybody—except the family they made out here.”

Across the U.S., the pandemic left record numbers of people without enough food. For many, charities and neighbors have become lifelines. For more, see the August issue's story "America’s Hunger Crisis" at the linkn in our bio.

node.text: Video by @bertiegregory / Basking sharks cruise at the surface on a feeding run near the Inner Hebrides, Scotland. Although they're the second biggest fish in the sea, these sharks have tiny prey. They eat zooplankton, with a particular preference for a group of tiny crustaceans called copepods. After locating a zooplankton patch, the sharks open their giant mouths and swim through it. Yum. node.text: Photos by @erintrieb / The recent fall of Afghanistan to the Taliban and the U.S. military’s August 31 withdrawal raised the stakes for thousands of Afghans who worked alongside American troops but never received their SIV (special immigration visa), needed to immigrate. The SIV program was initially approved in 2009 to assist Afghans, but a lengthy and often delayed approval process left tens of thousands—translators and other professionals employed by the U.S. military—stuck in Afghanistan, facing threats from the Taliban for their collaboration with the United States. Wahdat (surname not disclosed) served as an interpreter for the U.S. military. He's seen at his Kabul home, in 2016. He was waiting for his visa to come through, saying it was too dangerous for him to go into the city to work for fear of being recognized and targeted. In the second image, a bewildered Wahdat arrives for the first time in the U.S., at Reagan National Airport, in Washington, D.C., in July 2016. He now resides with his family in America. For more stories from Afghanistan, follow @erintrieb.

Photo by @simonnorfolkstudio / A view of the restored Malik cistern, in Herat. Just eight weeks ago I was working in Afghanistan, and I've never seen a set of my pictures become so redundant so fast. It seems like a dark tide has drowned this wonderful country and the things I photographed: the beautiful cultural heritage, unknown outside Afghanistan;  the newborn hope for the future; the gentle people I met and fell for. Life there was not perfect under American rule; it'll be worse under the Taliban, especially for women. I'm in despair watching the news, and I can think only of posting everything I have from my 20 years of photographing there. These pictures already feel like they are from a lost world. To see more images of Afghanistan and other material, follow me @simonnorfolkstudio.

node.text: Video by @joelsartore / Did you know that naked mole rats live in communities that are very similar in structure to those of many insects? Within these rodent colonies, there is one ruler—the queen. As is the case with some insect species, the queen is the only female member of the colony that breeds and bears young. Other rats in the colony serve as workers, digging burrows, collecting food, and tending to the queen’s needs. Check out more Photo Ark content by following @joelsartore. Video taken @lincolnchildrenszoo. #rat #molerat #rodent #PhotoArk #savetogether @insidenatgeo

node.text:
Photos by Stephen Alvarez @salvarezphoto / About 36,000 years ago, talented artists made paintings in southern France's Chauvet Cave. The images remain evocative to this day. The paintings also recorded images of an ice age world that is lost to us, except for the fossil record. In France lions, mammoths, rhinoceroses, and giant deer roamed the landscape. What we know of these two animals—the woolly rhino (Coelodonta antiquitatis) and the Megaloceros (Megaloceros giganteus)—comes through the archaeological record. We have their bones but we really did not know what they looked like before the discovery of cave paintings like Chauvet. The Megaloceros’s large, fatty hump and the woolly rhino’s distinctive band survived only in artwork. 

I founded the nonprofit @ancientartarchive to preserve and
share the world’s oldest artwork -images of forgotten worlds like this. Follow me @salvarezphoto and @ancientartarchive for more.

Photos by @lynseyaddario / These first two images are from the Dixie Fire, burning near the Butte Lake campground in the Northern California's Lassen National Forest, on August 26. The Dixie Fire, which has already burned over 820,000 acres (332,000 ha), is the second largest fire in California history. There are nearly 5,000 firefighters assigned to fight the fire, which is roughly 48% contained.

The last image is from the Caldor Fire, as it rips through the valley near the Sierra at Tahoe ski resort, south of Lake Tahoe, on  August 29. Dozens of houses burned along Highway 50, and the fire continues to travel in the area. The Caldor Fire has burned 200,000 acres (80,000 ha) and is 18% contained. On assignment for @natgeo. #Dixiefire #wildfires #climatechange @CALFIRE #lynseyaddario

node.text: Photo by @michaelchristopherbrown / Cubans watch the military convoy transporting Fidel Castro's ashes from Havana to Santiago, in December 2016. Along the thousand-kilometer (600 mi) route we saw very few stretches of road without people. They had traveled from north and south to watch the caravan pass—walking for miles or carried in by trucks, buses, or horse carriages to stand in remote areas, often dozens of miles from the nearest town. Fidel came to power in 1959 and died on November 25, 2016, at 90. His ashes were taken to the Santa Ifigenia Cemetery, where his brother Raúl placed the urn inside a giant boulder and behind a marble plaque inscribed simply with “Fidel,” next to the grave of Cuban independence hero José Martí. Follow @michaelchristopherbrown for more human stories from around the world.
